TextAreas can not be scrolled through when adding them to a ScrollPane. 
It has been discussed here: http://www.badlogicgames.com/forum/viewtopic.php?f=11&t=16323&p=70649
In the following piece of code, I use a Label and it is scrollable. If I replace:

ScrollPane pane = new ScrollPane(textLabel, defaultSkin);
~with~
ScrollPane pane = new ScrollPane(textArea, defaultSkin);

It is no longer scrollable. Here is the example code:

```
    final String reallyLongString = "a\na\na\na\na\na\na\na\na\na\na" +
    "\nb\nb\nb\nb\nb\nb\nb";
    final Label textLabel = new Label(reallyLongString, defaultSkin);
    textLabel.setAlignment(Align.center);
    textLabel.setWrap(true);
    TextArea textArea = new TextArea(reallyLongString, defaultSkin);
    ScrollPane pane = new ScrollPane(textLabel, defaultSkin);
    pane.setForceScroll(false, true);
    pane.setFlickScroll(false);
    pane.setOverscroll(false, true);
    Table table = new Table();
    table.add(pane).fill().expand();
    table.setBounds(0f, 20f, game.getWindowWidth(), 300f);
    gui.addActor(table);
    Gdx.input.setInputProcessor(gui);
    setIsCreated(true);
```

Currently default action for hide() in dialog is:
public void hide () {
        hide(sequence(fadeOut(0.4f, Interpolation.fade), Actions.removeListener(ignoreTouchDown, true), Actions.removeActor()));
    }

this action is processed by hide(Actor a) as:

addAction(sequence(action, Actions.removeListener(ignoreTouchDown, true), Actions.removeActor()));

so double remove happens, and this looks like dialog is not closing on 1st button touch or draw loop hangs (on 1 core android)...workaround is to overload:

@Override
            public void hide()
            {
                System.err.println("Hidding dialog");
                hide(sequence(Actions.fadeOut(0.4f, Interpolation.fade)));
            }

When serializing a String that contains a numerical value, such as "123", with the default OutputType.minimal, the output should contain the value withing quotes otherwise when it gets unserialized it will produce a different String value such as "123.0". Example:

``` java
public static class X { public String s; public X() {}; }

X x1 = new X();
x1.s = "123";
String jsonString = new Json().toJson(x1); // {s:123}
X x2 = new Json().fromJson(X.class, jsonString); // x2.s has value "123.0"
```

The value of x2.s is now "123.0", when it should be "123". The same problem happens for very large numbers like "1234567890123456789012" which gets converted to "1.2345678901234568e+21", which is very problematic as many services use such strings as identifiers.

One solution is to call setOutputType(JsonWriter.OutputType.javascript), but this is a workaround not a solution, and prevents other optimizations as well.

The ideal solution would be to change the JsonWriter.OutputType.quoteValue() method to also quote numerical strings. Since JsonWriter.OutputType is an enum not a class, it cannot be extended or customized without changing the LibGDX source code.

Currently:

```
/** Sets the minWidth and minHeight to the specified values. */
public Cell<T> minSize (float width, float height) {
    minSize(new Fixed(width));
    return this;
}
```

Should be:

```
/** Sets the minWidth and minHeight to the specified values. */
public Cell<T> minSize (float width, float height) {
            this.minWidth= new Fixed(width);
            this.minHeight= new Fixed(height);
    return this;
}
```

The same goes for the maxSize method.
